messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

- Full HTTP request path:
  /printshops/{id}/pricetable/papers

- All HTTP methods acceptable:
  false

- HEAD:
  false

- POST:
  true

- OPTIONS:
  false

- TRACE:
  false

- GET:
  false

- PUT:
  true

- DELETE:

- PATCH:

Explanation:
- The controller class has no class-level @RequestMapping, so the full path is exactly the value in the method-level @RequestMapping: "/printshops/{id}/pricetable/papers". The path parameter is named "id" as shown by @PathVariable(value = "id") long id.
- addNewPaperItem is annotated with @RequestMapping(..., method = RequestMethod.POST) â€” this explicitly enables POST on that path.
- editPaperItem in the same class is annotated with @RequestMapping(..., method = RequestMethod.PUT) and uses the identical path, so PUT is also explicitly enabled for the same path.
- No @RequestMapping or handler in this class declares GET, DELETE, PATCH, OPTIONS, TRACE, or HEAD for this path. Per the instruction to base acceptance "on the code, not on experiential assumptions," only methods explicitly mapped in the code are considered acceptable.
- Note: Spring can auto-handle HEAD when a GET mapping exists and may reply to OPTIONS at runtime, but since there is no GET or explicit OPTIONS mapping in the code for this path, those methods are reported as not acceptable here.
